---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Insurance for International Product Managers | Compare Expat Plans";
const description = "Health insurance guide for product managers working internationally, covering tech company PMs, startup product roles, remote product work, and global product leadership.";
const headline = "Insurance for International Product Managers";
const subheadline = "Coverage solutions for product managers building and shipping products across global tech companies and markets.";
const canonicalPath = "/guides/product-manager-insurance";
const heroBackgroundImage = "/images/guides/product-manager-insurance-hero.png";

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', label: 'Overview' },
  { id: 'coverage-needs', label: 'Coverage Needs' },
  { id: 'big-tech', label: 'Big Tech PMs' },
  { id: 'startup-pms', label: 'Startup PMs' },
  { id: 'remote-product', label: 'Remote Product Work' },
  { id: 'product-leadership', label: 'Product Leadership' },
  { id: 'work-demands', label: 'Work Demands' },
  { id: 'faqs', label: 'FAQs' },
  { id: 'next-steps', label: 'Next Steps' },
];
---

<PageShell 
  title={title} 
  description={description} 
  headline={headline}
  subheadline={subheadline}
  canonicalPath={canonicalPath}
  heroBackgroundImage={heroBackgroundImage}
  tocItems={tocItems}
>
  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
    
    <section id="overview">
      <h2>Global Product Management Careers</h2>
      <p>
        Product management has become a global profession. Tech companies build products serving worldwide users. Product teams distribute across time zones. PMs relocate to tech hubs or work remotely from anywhere. This creates careers with significant geographic flexibility and international scope.
      </p>
      <p>
        Product managers work at companies ranging from major tech firms with premium benefits to early-stage startups with minimal coverage. Remote work has expanded options further—work for a Bay Area company while living in Lisbon, or join a European startup from Asia.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide addresses insurance considerations for PMs at different company types and work arrangements—from big tech to startups, from office-based to fully remote.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="coverage-needs">
      <h2>Coverage Needs for Product Managers</h2>
      
      <ComparisonTable
        columns={[
          { key: 'need', header: 'Coverage Need' },
          { key: 'why', header: 'Why It Matters' },
          { key: 'typical', header: 'PM Industry?' },
        ]}
        rows={[
          { need: 'Mental health support', why: 'Product pressure, stakeholders', typical: 'Usually comprehensive' },
          { need: 'Location flexibility', why: 'Remote work options', typical: 'Increasingly common' },
          { need: 'Conference travel', why: 'Product events, user research', typical: 'Business travel covered' },
          { need: 'Vision and ergonomic', why: 'Screen-intensive work', typical: 'Generally included' },
          { need: 'Relocation support', why: 'Tech hub moves', typical: 'Assignment packages' },
          { need: 'Startup transition coverage', why: 'Job changes common', typical: 'Personal responsibility' },
        ]}
      />
      
      <h3>Tech Industry Benefits</h3>
      <p>
        Product management compensation is competitive, and benefits typically follow. Major tech companies provide comprehensive coverage as part of their talent strategy. However, coverage varies significantly across company sizes, funding stages, and geographic locations.
      </p>
      <p>
        PM careers often involve moving between companies as opportunities arise. Understanding coverage portability through job changes matters for professionals in a field where company tenure averages 2-3 years.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Knowledge Work Reality</h3>
      <p>
        Product management is demanding knowledge work—balancing stakeholder needs, making difficult trade-offs, and shipping under pressure. Mental health support matters for sustainable PM careers. Coverage should include robust mental health provisions.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="big-tech">
      <h2>Coverage at Big Tech Companies</h2>
      
      <h3>FAANG and Major Tech</h3>
      <p>
        Product managers at major tech companies—Google, Meta, Amazon, Apple, Microsoft—receive premium benefits. These companies compete for PM talent through total compensation including excellent health coverage. If you're at big tech, coverage is typically comprehensive.
      </p>
      <p>
        Big tech has international offices. Transfers between offices—Mountain View to London, Seattle to Singapore—typically include relocation packages with continued coverage. Verify specifics for your transfer situation.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Large Tech Companies</h3>
      <p>
        Beyond FAANG, large tech companies—Salesforce, Adobe, Uber, Airbnb, Stripe—provide strong benefits competing for product talent. Coverage quality at established tech companies is generally excellent, though specifics vary.
      </p>
      <p>
        These companies often support remote work arrangements. If working remotely from a different country than company headquarters, verify coverage works at your location.
      </p>
      
      <h3>International Tech Companies</h3>
      <p>
        Non-US tech companies—Spotify, Klarna, Revolut, Grab, Mercado Libre—have their own benefit structures reflecting their home market norms and international operations. Coverage quality varies; evaluate each company specifically.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Coverage for Product Managers"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for product managers working across global tech companies and markets."
      buttonText="Compare PM Plans"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

    <section id="startup-pms">
      <h2>Coverage at Startups</h2>
      
      <h3>Well-Funded Startups</h3>
      <p>
        Series B+ startups often provide competitive benefits to attract product talent from larger companies. Coverage at well-funded startups may approach big tech levels, though this varies by company and market.
      </p>
      <p>
        Startup benefits can change quickly—improving with funding rounds or declining with runway concerns. Personal coverage provides stability through startup volatility.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Early-Stage Startups</h3>
      <p>
        Seed and Series A startups may offer equity-heavy compensation with limited benefits. Early-stage PM roles trade current benefits for potential equity upside. Evaluate what coverage you'd need to arrange personally if startup benefits are minimal.
      </p>
      <p>
        Startup failure is common. If your startup doesn't succeed, employer coverage ends. Personal coverage provides continuity through the uncertainty inherent in early-stage startup work.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Founding PM Roles</h3>
      <p>
        First PM hires at startups may have significant influence on product direction but minimal formal benefits. These roles may resemble founder situations more than employee roles. See our startup founder guide for coverage considerations at this stage.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="remote-product">
      <h2>Remote Product Work</h2>
      
      <h3>Remote-First Companies</h3>
      <p>
        Remote-first companies—GitLab, Zapier, Automattic—build distributed teams by design. These companies typically provide coverage appropriate for globally distributed employees. Verify coverage works in your specific location.
      </p>
      <p>
        Remote-first culture often means location flexibility. You may be able to work from various countries. Coverage should support this flexibility without restricting your location options.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Remote Work from Abroad</h3>
      <p>
        Some PMs work remotely for US companies while living abroad—digital nomad style or established in another country. Employer coverage may or may not work at your international location. Verify specifically, and supplement with personal coverage if needed.
      </p>
      <p>
        Tax and employment law complexity may affect how remote international work is structured. Coverage arrangements may depend on whether you're an employee, contractor, or employed through an EOR (Employer of Record).
      </p>
      
      <h3>Nomadic Product Work</h3>
      <p>
        Some PMs work while traveling—true location independence. This requires coverage functioning across multiple countries. Plans designed for digital nomads work better than location-specific coverage for mobile PM lifestyles.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="product-leadership">
      <h2>Product Leadership Roles</h2>
      
      <h3>Directors and VPs</h3>
      <p>
        Product leadership roles—Director of Product, VP Product, CPO—typically include premium benefits. Senior roles at established companies come with comprehensive coverage. Leadership compensation negotiations may include enhanced benefits.
      </p>
      <p>
        Product leaders often travel more than individual PMs—visiting distributed teams, attending board meetings, meeting enterprise customers. Coverage should handle this increased business travel.
      </p>
      
      <h3>International Product Leadership</h3>
      <p>
        Leading product for international markets may involve relocating to regional hubs or traveling extensively. Regional product leadership—EMEA, APAC, LATAM—requires coverage working throughout your region.
      </p>
      <p>
        Global product roles involve coordinating across time zones and occasional travel to team locations worldwide. Coverage should support this global product leadership pattern.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Consulting and Advisory</h3>
      <p>
        Product consultants and advisors—fractional CPOs, product coaches—arrange their own coverage. Consulting income can support quality coverage, but consultants must actively choose and purchase insurance.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-demands">
      <h2>Managing Work Demands</h2>
      
      <h3>Product Pressure</h3>
      <p>
        Product management involves constant pressure—shipping deadlines, stakeholder demands, metrics accountability, difficult trade-offs. This creates stress affecting health. Coverage should include mental health support for managing ongoing PM pressure.
      </p>
      <p>
        Launch periods intensify pressure. Major releases, pivots, and critical milestones create acute stress. Coverage should support health management during these demanding periods.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Meeting-Heavy Schedules</h3>
      <p>
        PMs often have meeting-heavy calendars—syncs with engineering, design reviews, stakeholder alignments, user research. Finding time for healthcare appointments requires flexibility. Telehealth options help manage health despite packed schedules.
      </p>
      <p>
        Global product roles mean meetings across time zones. Unusual hours affect sleep and wellbeing. Coverage should support health management despite demanding global schedules.
      </p>
      
      <h3>Screen-Intensive Work</h3>
      <p>
        Product work involves extensive screen time—documents, dashboards, meetings, prototypes. Vision care, ergonomic support, and RSI prevention matter for sustainable PM careers. Verify coverage addresses these knowledge work health needs.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="faqs">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      
      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm a PM at a big tech company. Do I need additional coverage?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Big tech typically provides comprehensive coverage. Review your specific benefits. You likely don't need supplemental coverage unless you have needs not addressed by your employer plan, like coverage during extended international stays beyond business travel.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm joining an early-stage startup. What should I expect?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Early-stage startup benefits vary widely. Ask specifically about health coverage during the offer process. If coverage is minimal, factor personal insurance costs into your compensation evaluation. Don't assume startup benefits match big tech.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I work remotely from another country. Is my US employer coverage valid?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Employer coverage may or may not work internationally—verify specifically for your situation. Some plans cover employees working abroad; others have geographic restrictions. If employer coverage doesn't work at your location, personal international health insurance fills the gap.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm relocating for a PM role. Is my family covered?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Relocation packages typically include family coverage. Verify specifically: spouse and children coverage, how coverage works at your new location, and any waiting periods. Get documentation before accepting relocation.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Does coverage include mental health for PM pressure?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Tech company coverage typically includes mental health benefits. Big tech often provides robust mental health support—therapy, EAP programs, wellness resources. Verify specifics for your employer. Mental health coverage matters for sustainable PM careers.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I change jobs frequently. How do I maintain coverage?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            PM careers often involve job changes. Employer coverage typically transitions with employment—old coverage ends, new coverage begins. Mind gap periods between jobs. COBRA bridges gaps but is expensive. Personal coverage provides continuity independent of employment.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="next-steps">
      <h2>Next Steps</h2>
      <p>
        Start by understanding your current coverage based on your employer and work arrangement. Big tech PMs likely have comprehensive coverage. Startup PMs should verify what's actually provided. Remote international workers should confirm coverage works at their location.
      </p>
      <p>
        Product management careers offer exciting opportunities to shape products used by millions. Your coverage should support this work—enabling focus on building great products without healthcare concerns, whether you're shipping features from headquarters or a beach in Bali.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Protect Your Product Career"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for product managers working across global tech companies and markets."
      buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

  </article>
</PageShell>
